  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">104002</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1389177/files/sxpiping.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00000 A schematic diagram of the solid xenon test stand~</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">11989</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1389177/files/sxgrowingrate4.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00001 A simple thermal model of the expected solid xenon growth (red curve), and an example of actual growth of solid xenon (blue dots). The temperatures at the bottom and top of the liquid xenon volume are set to 145 and 161 K, respectively. The disagreement between the ideal 1-dimensional thermal model (red curve) and actual growing speed (blue dots) might be due to different thermal configuration of the realistic xenon glass cylinder and the local convection effect of the liquid xenon above the solid xenon.~</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">224280</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1389177/files/frostlayer.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00003 Photographs of various types of solid xenon. The top left photo shows a concave structure of the solid surface due to the over-cooling at the barrel. There is also an opaque substructure at the bottom center due to the significant temperature gradient at the bottom surface. These are produced when there was a rapid variation of cooling liquid level. The top right photo shows frozen layers of solid xenon. These structures can be easily created when the pressure drops below the vapor pressure. The bottom photo shows solid xenon in a polycrystalline state on the order of a few mm, provided when the temperature and pressure control become unstable near the triple point (161.4\,K and 11.9 PSIA). The dark brown color at the bottom of the chamber is kapton tape. The spacing of the heater between each wire is about 1\,cm, which is a good measure of the approximate height of xenon.~</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">253558</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1389177/files/opaquexenon.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00005 Photographs of opaque solid xenon (left) and transparent solid xenon (right). The left photograph shows about 3\,cm of opaque solid xenon and 1\,cm of liquid xenon above the solid phase. The right photograph shows about 3\,cm high (about 650\,g) of transparent solid xenon and 1\,cm (about 189.4\,g) high  liquid xenon on top of the solid xenon.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">262000</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1389177/files/transparentxenon.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00006 Photographs of opaque solid xenon (left) and transparent solid xenon (right). The left photograph shows about 3\,cm of opaque solid xenon and 1\,cm of liquid xenon above the solid phase. The right photograph shows about 3\,cm high (about 650\,g) of transparent solid xenon and 1\,cm (about 189.4\,g) high  liquid xenon on top of the solid xenon.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">351241</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1389177/files/xenontpc.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00007 The time projection chamber (TPC) installed in the xenon glass chamber. In this particular sample, the amount of solid xenon in the chamber is about $\sim$2\,kg. A little opaque area near the surface of the glass bottom edge is cryogenic epoxy. In this particular sample, some birefringence can be seen at the inner glass wall near the grid rings.~</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">371596</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1389177/files/concavexenon.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00002 Photographs of various types of solid xenon. The top left photo shows a concave structure of the solid surface due to the over-cooling at the barrel. There is also an opaque substructure at the bottom center due to the significant temperature gradient at the bottom surface. These are produced when there was a rapid variation of cooling liquid level. The top right photo shows frozen layers of solid xenon. These structures can be easily created when the pressure drops below the vapor pressure. The bottom photo shows solid xenon in a polycrystalline state on the order of a few mm, provided when the temperature and pressure control become unstable near the triple point (161.4\,K and 11.9 PSIA). The dark brown color at the bottom of the chamber is kapton tape. The spacing of the heater between each wire is about 1\,cm, which is a good measure of the approximate height of xenon.~</subfield>
  </datafield>
